\begin_layout Standard
Several quantum mechanical phenomena can be described in terms of simple
 harmonic 
\series bold
oscillators
\series default
 modified by the inclusion of linear friction.
 For example, deep inelastic scattering and field-theoretic formulations
 of fundamental anyons can be so modelled.
 It has recently been shown 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kang07"

\end_inset

 that squeezed light entering quantum optics can be statewise identified
 up to automorphisms with damped simple harmonic oscillators.
 An understanding of such oscillators is therefore of use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The frictionally damped simple harmonic oscillator can be expressed in a
 Lagrangian formulation only with the addition of a second variable of motion.
 A suitable Lagrangian is known to be 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kang07"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L=m\dot{x}\dot{y}+\frac{R}{2}(x\dot{y}-\dot{x}y)-kxy\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

